The paper proposes a novel adversarial learning framework for estimating individual treatment effect (ITE) in the presence of latent confounders. This involves using noisy proxies for the latent confounders to make an unbiased estimate of the ITE. The paper draws on concepts from machine learning, such as adversarial learning, to develop the framework. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science). The paper also deals with statistical issues related to confounding bias, which suggests that it could be relevant to cs.ST (Statistics) and cs.IT (Information Theory).
